\begin_layout Standard
The model specified in the chapter considers how consumers observing a common
 reference point and a macroeconomic process would project their long-term
 future relative wealth and make different decisions for purchases of assets
 and status enhancing goods based on their private risk-aversion levels.
 The two kinds of status items in the model are a risky upside investment
 and a protection against untoward circumstances in face of uncertainty
 observed in the macroeconomy.
 The consumers optimise their expected wealth subject to their risk aversions
 with a PT like function
\bar under
.
 There are two questions that we attempt to answer with the approach.
 First is whether the reference points applicable to such a competition
 are implied by the average long-term returns in the economy or not.
 Second, whether the too much risk in a competition discourage status consumptio
n marked by wide differences in wealth could discourage status competitions
 - and thereby making a common reference point infeasible.
\end_layout

